00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,519
Now, here we go.

2
00:00:01,519 --> 00:00:07,159
This time, we've got something else to read and think about.

3
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:13,080
And I intend to do Yvonne's rebellion.

4
00:00:13,399 --> 00:00:17,560
It's just about what you can cover in one lecture.

5
00:00:17,560 --> 00:00:23,560
And it's very interesting and very important and existentialist.

6
00:00:23,560 --> 00:00:30,759
It reveals a lot about Dostoevsky's philosophy and a lot about Yvonne all at the same time.

7
00:00:30,759 --> 00:00:57,959
Just to remember where we are, Yvonne is the one who wants to be perfect, to get rid of the base, earthy, dark, sensual, Karamatsov side of himself and become a refined, abstract, pure person who is self-sufficient and observer, not involved, observer, eyewitness of what's going on.

8
00:00:58,279 --> 00:01:04,120
It comes out, too, in lots of little ways, how he doesn't want to get involved with anybody.

9
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:15,559
On 223, he's starting to tell Alyasha his intimate life sort of stance.

10
00:01:15,560 --> 00:01:23,399
And he tells him something which only Yvonne would think at the top of 223.

11
00:01:23,399 --> 00:01:27,720
He says, I want to get to know you once and for all, and I want you to know me.

12
00:01:27,720 --> 00:01:29,320
And then we will say goodbye.

13
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:33,079
I believe it's always best to get to know people just before leaving them.

14
00:01:33,079 --> 00:01:52,720
That is, not to get involved, not to get hurt, not to get, that is, you may know people like that who just at the end of vacation or just at the end of the school year, or you will be able to get close to them only because they know that they're going to go away and everything, and not, and so are in some sense safe.

15
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:59,679
So Ivan wants to tell Alyasha everything as long as they don't get involved.

16
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:05,600
And he wants to tell him this sort of existentialist thing.

17
00:02:06,079 --> 00:02:13,360
He wants to tell him the middle of 228, I'm trying to explain as quickly as possible my essential nature.

18
00:02:13,359 --> 00:02:18,560
That is what manner of man I am, what I believe in, and for what I hope.

19
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:19,919
That's it, isn't it?

20
00:02:19,919 --> 00:02:31,120
And he wants to give Alyasha his existentialist stance, which he succeeds very well in doing in the course of the following discussion.

21
00:02:31,599 --> 00:02:35,839
And it's not taught, it isn't really even telling him what he believes.

22
00:02:35,839 --> 00:02:37,440
It's something deeper than that.

23
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:44,159
It's telling him how he relates to the world, how he lives, that he wants to explain.

24
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:53,279
And he says that, he starts to explain that on page 223.

25
00:02:53,279 --> 00:02:59,200
And this long speech I have to read because it's complicated what Yvonne's relation is.

26
00:02:59,199 --> 00:03:02,720
It isn't just that he's an observer.

27
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:08,799
It's, well, you'll see when I read it, a little below the middle of 223.

28
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:32,560
Do you know, I've been sitting here thinking to myself that if I didn't believe in life, if I lost faith in the woman I love, that's Katerina, lost faith in the order of things, or convinced, in fact, that everything is a disorderly, damnable, and perhaps devil-ridden chaos, which in a way he does believe, if I were struck by every horror of man's disillusionment, still I would want to live.

29
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:40,040
That is, he's enough involved in life that he can't just get out of it.

30
00:03:41,079 --> 00:03:45,880
But having once tasted of the cup, I would not turn away from it.

31
00:03:45,880 --> 00:03:47,719
The cup is the cup of life.

32
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:49,560
He's talking all these metaphors.

33
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:52,360
I would not turn away from it till I had drained it.

34
00:03:52,360 --> 00:04:01,800
That is, he wants to get everything he can out of life before he turns away from it, and he means to commit suicide, it turns out, at 30.

35
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:09,399
At 30, though, I shall be sure to leave the cup, even if I've not emptied it, and turn away where I do not know.

36
00:04:09,399 --> 00:04:16,279
Although he certainly sort of knows that he's got to, and he wants to kill himself.

37
00:04:16,839 --> 00:04:23,159
But till I'm 30, I know that my youth will triumph over everything, every disillusionment, every disgust with life.

38
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:30,120
I've asked myself many times whether there is in the world any despair that could overcome this frantic thirst for life.

39
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:33,480
See, that's the Karamatsov in him he can't get rid of.

40
00:04:33,479 --> 00:04:37,079
And I've come to the conclusion that there isn't, that is till I'm 30.

41
00:04:37,399 --> 00:05:01,480
And then he thinks he will, because this Karamatsov sensuality and search for life and love of, as he says at the top of 224, the sticky little leaves in the spring and so forth, the blue sky, all this attractive side of the world that attracts Yvonne and makes him attractive.

42
00:05:02,280 --> 00:05:05,320
He can't get over it, but he wants to.

43
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:10,680
And when he does, at 30, then he'll get out of the world somehow.

44
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:18,360
And so, and he seems to love people.

45
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:20,639
It's sort of hard to get a fix on that.

46
00:05:20,199 --> 00:05:23,280
He seems to be loving Katerina.

47
00:05:24,159 --> 00:05:29,680
And when he's talking to her, it looks like he has this sensual, earthy side.

48
00:05:30,159 --> 00:05:34,399
But he also says at one point he's never understood loving his neighbors.

49
00:05:34,399 --> 00:05:37,440
And Fedor says that Ivan never loved anyone.

50
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:39,120
I think that's sort of true.

51
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:43,440
And he certainly has no unconditioned commitment to anyone but himself.

52
00:05:43,440 --> 00:05:52,719
Because if he found himself really getting involved with someone, so that they were the important thing in his life, gave his life meaning, he would be in terrible shape.

53
00:05:52,719 --> 00:05:55,040
He wants to be autonomous.

54
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:58,400
He wants to be a self-made and independent person.

55
00:05:58,399 --> 00:06:06,880
So I think he loves people as much as you can love people and still be a completely safe, independent person.

56
00:06:07,519 --> 00:06:10,639
And that's so much for that.

57
00:06:11,519 --> 00:06:24,799
He considers then, in a funny way, his involvement in the world, his sensual side, his Karamatsov life, as not essential and somehow bad.

58
00:06:25,120 --> 00:06:28,320
And it's not essential because he can get rid of it.

59
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:38,719
He may have to kill himself to get rid of it, but he's not going to let it determine what he does, at least not after as soon as he can get free of it at 30.

60
00:06:38,719 --> 00:06:42,080
Now that's not altogether crucial.

61
00:06:42,639 --> 00:06:44,800
What's crucial is what follows.

62
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:56,079
That is, what he explains to Alyasha is his basic stance on the world, why he has to get out of it when he's 30.

63
00:06:57,199 --> 00:07:11,000
And why that given his sort of honorable, moral, pure attitude, it's just impossible for him to stay around in this world.

64
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:28,440
And that's, and first, before I can explain that, and he can, before he can explain that to Alyasha, he's got to make a distinction, which is a very existentialist Pascalian distinction.

65
00:07:28,440 --> 00:07:32,040
He's not going to discuss whether God exists or not.

66
00:07:32,040 --> 00:07:42,280
He says we're just not capable with our finite, everyday human minds to grasp whether God exists or not.

67
00:07:42,280 --> 00:07:47,080
Pascal starts this like so many other important existentialist things.

68
00:07:47,079 --> 00:07:51,000
Pascal has this wonderful idea in the PensÃ©es.

69
00:07:50,999 --> 00:07:54,360
He doesn't say you can't prove the existence of God.

70
00:07:54,359 --> 00:08:04,440
He says you can prove the existence of God and you can prove the non-existence of God, which is just a very interesting and true philosophical thing to say.

71
00:08:04,440 --> 00:08:11,000
Philosophers have come up with all sorts of interesting proofs of the existence of God and all sorts of interesting proofs of the non-existence.

72
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:14,920
And what Pascal thinks is that just shows the limits of human reason.

73
00:08:14,920 --> 00:08:16,839
And that's exactly what Yvonne thinks.

74
00:08:16,839 --> 00:08:27,399
He says, at the bottom 228, about a third of the page up, I have a Euclidean earthly mind, and so how can I solve problems which are not of the world?

75
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:32,280
And I advise you never to think about it either, Alyasha, especially about God, whether he exists or not.

76
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:34,199
And Alyasha never does.

77
00:08:35,160 --> 00:08:40,600
All such questions are utterly inappropriate for a mind created with an idea of only three dimensions.

78
00:08:40,599 --> 00:08:42,119
And so I accept God.

79
00:08:42,359 --> 00:08:43,880
He doesn't really care.

80
00:08:43,879 --> 00:08:49,639
I mean, that's just, for the sake of the argument, in effect, for the sake of the argument, I accept God.

81
00:08:49,640 --> 00:08:50,520
I'm glad to.

82
00:08:50,520 --> 00:08:55,199
And what's more, I accept his wisdom, his purpose, which is completely beyond our knowledge.

83
00:08:51,160 --> 00:08:58,160
But he's going to make a different sort of argument, he says.

84
00:08:58,800 --> 00:09:02,000
And that's the argument that he's about to give Gabrielle.

85
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:05,120
Gabrielle's the name of my daughter.

86
00:09:05,119 --> 00:09:08,159
I don't know how she got into this, into my head today.

87
00:09:08,160 --> 00:09:11,760
I haven't even talked to her on the phone or anything for a few days.

88
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:15,199
But anyway, if I keep saying Gabrielle, I always mean Yvonne.

89
00:09:15,199 --> 00:09:17,280
What the connection is, is beyond me.

90
00:09:19,599 --> 00:09:32,560
Now we have to go into his argument, which is his defense of a certain philosophical position, but not just a philosophical position, but a certain way of life that he wants to defend.

91
00:09:32,560 --> 00:09:38,480
And that's what he starts talking about on 229 at the top.

92
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:41,280
Yet, would you believe it in the final result?

93
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:44,799
I don't accept this world of God's, although I know it exists.

94
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:46,160
I don't accept it at all.

95
00:09:46,160 --> 00:09:48,479
It's not that I don't accept God, you must understand.

96
00:09:48,479 --> 00:09:52,320
It's the world created by Him I don't and cannot accept.

97
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:55,440
And that's very, I mean, that's a kind of existentialist point.

98
00:09:55,440 --> 00:09:58,399
It doesn't really matter whether the Supreme Being exists.

99
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:05,360
Remember, Kierkegaard got rid of the Supreme Being already, and he was a, and yet he thought faith was very important.

100
00:10:05,359 --> 00:10:15,440
It's a question of faith is about how you live in the world and how involved you will be in the world and in what way you will be involved in the world.

101
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:26,240
And Yvonne has a very strong view that he does not accept the usual Christian way of being in the world.

102
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:27,680
That's what he rejects.

103
00:10:27,680 --> 00:10:34,400
And now we're going to find out what he means.

104
00:10:34,719 --> 00:10:49,480
He's going to prove that any decent person is obliged to leave the world as soon as possible, as soon as they get over this young, sensual love of everything, which he sort of has.

105
00:10:49,479 --> 00:10:53,880
And the question is for Ivan, why should you do that?

106
00:10:53,879 --> 00:10:55,719
Well, he's going to tell us why.

107
00:10:56,040 --> 00:11:00,760
And he has a rather complicated argument, not terribly.

108
00:11:00,760 --> 00:11:13,240
And he's going to tell us, you know, he's going to argue, he's going to give evidence that the world is such a corrupt and evil place that no moral person could accept living in it.

109
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:14,839
That's his rebellion.

110
00:11:15,160 --> 00:11:19,320
That's his rejection of the world.

111
00:11:19,560 --> 00:11:28,280
And you should be asking yourself, because Dostoevsky wants you to take this book seriously and to take the arguments in the book seriously.

112
00:11:28,280 --> 00:11:35,240
You have to ask yourself, as you hear this argument right now, and as you read it, are you convinced?

113
00:11:35,239 --> 00:11:37,959
Are you going to commit suicide at the age of 30?

114
00:11:37,959 --> 00:11:41,079
And if not, where's the flaw in his argument?

115
00:11:41,079 --> 00:11:43,160
It's pretty convincing.

116
00:11:43,160 --> 00:11:46,280
It even convinces Alyasha, as you'll see.

117
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:48,600
And that's very interesting.

118
00:11:48,599 --> 00:11:51,480
Okay, and so here we go.

119
00:11:51,479 --> 00:12:00,119
He says he's been collecting a dossier of child abuse, in effect, atrocities committed against children.

120
00:12:00,839 --> 00:12:07,160
And he's got, and that's going to be the sort of basis of his case against the world.

121
00:12:07,160 --> 00:12:13,400
On 232, at the middle of the page, roughly, he says, I like to collect certain facts.

122
00:12:13,400 --> 00:12:14,680
And would you believe?

123
00:12:14,680 --> 00:12:18,600
I even copy anecdotes of a certain sort from newspapers and books.

124
00:12:18,599 --> 00:12:20,760
I've got a fine collection.

125
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:24,480
I think fine is not quite the right translation, though.

126
00:12:24,479 --> 00:12:25,600
I can't explain why.

127
00:12:21,079 --> 00:12:26,720
But you just take my word for it.

128
00:12:26,879 --> 00:12:29,840
He should be saying, I've got a nice collection.

129
00:12:29,839 --> 00:12:38,480
Now, why, what the difference is between a fine and a nice is so all right, but you'll see that it fits.

130
00:12:38,479 --> 00:12:41,760
And next time he talks about this, he does say nice.

131
00:12:41,760 --> 00:12:45,840
Fine makes it sound too much like it's fine art.

132
00:12:45,839 --> 00:12:48,480
That's not what he's got.

133
00:12:49,440 --> 00:12:51,120
So let's go on.

134
00:12:53,359 --> 00:13:00,960
And first, he has to get rid of two objections to his argument: that there is all this evil because everybody deserves it.

135
00:13:00,959 --> 00:13:03,680
They've done bad things and now they're being punished.

136
00:13:03,680 --> 00:13:16,240
And the second is that even though this world is full of bad things, even for people who don't deserve it, and good things for people who should be being punished, that's going to be made up for in the afterlife.

137
00:13:16,239 --> 00:13:22,640
That is, the bad people are ultimately going to get punished for eternity, and the good people are going to get rewarded for eternity.

138
00:13:22,639 --> 00:13:27,599
So this little sort of wobble in the system doesn't matter.

139
00:13:27,599 --> 00:13:30,000
It's all going to be fixed in the end.

140
00:13:30,320 --> 00:13:36,559
So his answer to that, as you should remember, is: well, children are innocent.

141
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:45,680
You can't say of children that they've done something wrong, and that's why there can be child abuse and they can be tortured and so forth.

142
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:55,279
They don't know right and wrong until they're seven, turns out to be the view that Dostoevsky accepts from the Russian Orthodox Church.

143
00:13:55,440 --> 00:14:02,320
That isn't that children don't do bad and nasty things before they're seven, but they don't really know that they're bad and nasty things.

144
00:14:02,320 --> 00:14:04,560
They don't understand good and evil.

145
00:14:04,560 --> 00:14:06,760
Augustine is interesting about this.

146
00:14:06,760 --> 00:14:13,000
Augustine wants to argue both that children are innocent and that there is some kind of original sinfulness.

147
00:14:12,999 --> 00:14:35,720
And he has this example of how children are sinful from the start because he says, a sibling who has already had all the milk that he or she can take from the mother will be jealous and upset when the other sibling gets the breast and the milk.

148
00:14:35,719 --> 00:14:42,120
And that kind of jealousy and upsetness is sin all the way back, Augustine says.

149
00:14:42,119 --> 00:14:44,360
And that's probably okay.

150
00:14:44,839 --> 00:14:51,320
And Dostoevsky would just say, yes, but that's not the same as doing something wrong that you know is wrong.

151
00:14:51,320 --> 00:14:53,320
And children don't do that.

152
00:14:53,320 --> 00:14:58,120
Children are basically sweet and attractive.

153
00:14:58,119 --> 00:15:01,799
That's a bit of an exaggeration for Yvonne.

154
00:15:01,800 --> 00:15:02,920
How old is Kolya?

155
00:15:02,920 --> 00:15:04,199
Does anybody remember?

156
00:15:04,199 --> 00:15:05,959
Who is not at all sweet and attractive?

157
00:15:06,040 --> 00:15:07,880
He's over seven, though.

158
00:15:07,879 --> 00:15:09,399
And I think Kolya's about 12.

159
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:10,440
Keep your eyes open.

160
00:15:10,439 --> 00:15:13,959
Kolya's a test child later in the book.

161
00:15:14,200 --> 00:15:16,439
It plays a big role.

162
00:15:17,079 --> 00:15:18,999
But it isn't Kolya, it's Alyusha.

163
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:20,679
Yeah, keep your eyes open for Alysa.

164
00:15:20,679 --> 00:15:23,399
He's younger, and he's the test child.

165
00:15:23,399 --> 00:15:30,040
And we'll see if he's nice and gentle and loving, as Yvonne thinks.

166
00:15:30,040 --> 00:15:40,999
I think Yvonne is supposed to be sort of not knowing anything about children up close, making this special nice picture of children for reasons that will become obvious in a minute.

167
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,480
So they're supposed to be sweet and lovable, and yet they're made to suffer.

168
00:15:45,480 --> 00:15:49,800
This is on 231, at about eight lines down.

169
00:15:49,800 --> 00:15:55,119
But in the first place, children can be loved even at close quarters, even when they're dirty, even when they're ugly.

170
00:15:51,079 --> 00:15:55,920
He doesn't really know.

171
00:15:56,240 --> 00:16:06,399
The second reason why I would speak of grown-ups of grown-up people is that besides being disgusting and unworthy of love, they have a compensation.

172
00:16:06,399 --> 00:16:08,880
They've eaten the fruit and no good and evil.

173
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:10,800
They've become like gods.

174
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:20,399
What he's saying is if older people are hurt and tortured and suffer, it's probably because, or it must be because, they've done something wrong.

175
00:16:20,399 --> 00:16:27,679
But children suffer, and they haven't or done anything wrong in the sense that they're innocent.

176
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:30,960
These are these younger than sevens.

177
00:16:31,280 --> 00:16:36,399
On 235, he tells this story.

178
00:16:36,720 --> 00:16:48,560
He tells lots of stories about people who torture children, kill children in front of the eyes of their mother, beat up their own children, whip them, and so forth.

179
00:16:48,879 --> 00:16:59,359
And then at the bottom of 234, having told a lot of horror stories already, he says, but I have still better things about children.

180
00:16:59,359 --> 00:17:01,439
Those are those nice things.

181
00:17:02,639 --> 00:17:05,519
A great, great deal about Russian children, Alyasha.

182
00:17:05,520 --> 00:17:16,880
There was a little girl of five who was hated by her father and mother, worthy and respectable people, and so forth, and they torture her in some way.

183
00:17:16,879 --> 00:17:18,239
I forget how.

184
00:17:18,240 --> 00:17:19,439
It doesn't matter.

185
00:17:20,720 --> 00:17:30,879
But what matters at the end of that paragraph, he said, in every man, of course, a demon lies hidden, the demon of rage, the demon of lustful heat at the screams of the tortured victim.

186
00:17:30,879 --> 00:17:33,280
We'll come back to that in a while.

187
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:42,919
But right now, there's evil in the world, and it's people hurting innocent children.

188
00:17:43,240 --> 00:17:50,040
And Yvonne thinks that the answer that will get fixed in another world isn't any solution, which is interesting.

189
00:17:50,040 --> 00:17:54,919
One, it doesn't help to punish the abusers.

190
00:17:54,919 --> 00:18:01,719
It just adds more suffering, but that's not going to help the ones who were suffering.

191
00:18:01,720 --> 00:18:03,239
And what about them?

192
00:18:03,240 --> 00:18:07,560
Well, it doesn't help to reward the children since they've already suffered.

193
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:19,719
This is this kind of Kierkegaardian point that it's not going to help them while they're being tortured in various ways to say, well, when I get back and get into paradise, this is all going to look okay to me.

194
00:18:20,119 --> 00:18:24,520
It isn't okay when you're in it and you can't see it from the point of view of the future.

195
00:18:24,520 --> 00:18:39,399
So it doesn't help anybody that even if there were a God and even if in the afterlife everything was ironed out, it wouldn't justify the suffering that people actually, children, go through.

196
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:45,719
So this is when he says in 238, a higher harmony wouldn't help.

197
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:48,839
And that's about the middle of the page.

198
00:18:49,639 --> 00:18:50,839
Let's see.

199
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:53,320
Yeah, the middle of the page.

200
00:18:54,280 --> 00:18:56,680
I renounce the higher harmony altogether.

201
00:18:56,679 --> 00:19:09,159
It's not worth the tears of that one tortured child who beat itself on the breast with its little fist and prayed in its stinking outhouse with tears to the dear God and so forth.

202
00:19:09,159 --> 00:19:13,960
He says further down at the bottom, I don't want harmony from love of humanity.

