788
01:10:45,160 --> 01:10:46,599
I can write that on the board.

789
01:10:46,599 --> 01:10:55,240
It's a philosophical kind of argument, which I'll explain how it works in a minute, and it's along the diagram that you've got.

790
01:10:55,240 --> 01:10:57,000
So see how to spell it.

791
01:10:57,880 --> 01:11:00,039
And isn't that right?

792
01:11:00,359 --> 01:11:00,919
Yeah.

793
01:11:03,160 --> 01:11:13,399
In an antinomy, you get two opposite views which are presented as the only possible alternatives.

794
01:11:13,399 --> 01:11:21,079
And then you show each side argues for its truth by showing that the other side is hopeless, can't be right.

795
01:11:21,080 --> 01:11:26,200
So in Kant, whom I mention every once in a while, but never, did I ever write on the board?

796
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:27,320
I probably did at some point.

797
01:11:27,399 --> 01:11:35,879
They say, Kant has a whole section of the critique of pure reason called the antinomies, and he gives four of them.

798
01:11:35,880 --> 01:11:38,999
But I just give you one for an example.

799
01:11:39,000 --> 01:12:02,719
So, if you think that the only two alternatives about space are that space goes on forever, or else it's finite, you discover that neither view is tolerable, and you show you can the if you think space goes on forever, then the other side can point out that that's impossible.

800
01:12:02,719 --> 01:12:11,679
That would be something like an actual infinite, but in infinite isn't a sort of big number, there can't be an actual infinite, so there must be a limit to space.

801
01:12:11,679 --> 01:12:20,399
And the other side says, Okay, but then so then the other side comes back and says, Yeah, but what would there be on the other side of this limit?

802
01:12:20,399 --> 01:12:21,599
I used to worry about that.

803
01:12:24,080 --> 01:12:30,160
You come to the edge of space and then you look to see if there's anything on the other side, and it looks like there's more space out there.

804
01:12:30,160 --> 01:12:32,479
So, and Kant thinks there's a third position.

805
01:12:32,479 --> 01:12:33,599
I'm not going to tell you what it is.

806
01:12:33,599 --> 01:12:36,320
You could take the Kant course later if you want to find out.

807
01:12:36,320 --> 01:12:42,079
But the whole, and you get the same thing with time: is there a beginning of time?

808
01:12:42,080 --> 01:12:48,639
Well, if there isn't, time has been going on forever, but forever is too big for anything ever to be.

809
01:12:48,639 --> 01:12:50,639
So, it must have started somewhere.

810
01:12:50,639 --> 01:12:51,599
But then, when?

811
01:12:51,599 --> 01:12:55,919
And, you know, and when in time, and how did it get started?

812
01:12:55,920 --> 01:12:58,799
And that doesn't make any sense either.

813
01:12:59,120 --> 01:13:11,039
So, antinomies are positions which each side argues against the other side by showing that the other side is untenable, so they must be right.

814
01:13:11,040 --> 01:13:18,639
And the only way to fix an antinomy is to find that there's a third possibility that hasn't been considered.

